.","meanings":["Irish:","shortened form of   Shanahan  .","shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Seanáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Seanán</i>’, a personal name based on a pet form of <i>seán</i> ‘old’. This Irish surname became established in Scotland in the 14th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Shanahan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamonn, Aidan, Donovan, Kieran, Liam, Marypat, Siobhan.","Irish (Tipperary and Limerick): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Seanacháin</b> or <b>Mac Seanacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Seanachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Seanach</i>, a personal name from <i>sean</i> ‘ancient, old’."]},{"name":"Synan","meanings":["Irish (County Cork): according to Woulfe, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sionáin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Seanáin</b> (see   Shannon  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Shannon was born in 1420, in Ireland, Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Rosetta Fisher. He died in Ennistimon, County Clare, Ireland."},"et":{"1420–Deceased":"1420–Surnud","1423–Female":"1423–Surnud","1443–1489":"1443–1489","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1489":"1489","1423":"1423","1443":"1443","1420":"1420","Ennistimon, County Clare, Irela